description.narrative: In 2017, during the first year of the project with the Guyana Revenue Authority (GRA), advisors provided guidance in building robust anti-corruption measures, implementing HR reforms, organizational restructuring, and developing capacity for basic and specialized industry audits, in preparation for significant offshore petroleum reserves coming online. The GRA has established a Special Investigations Unit, hired new investigative staff, and agreed to implement a related action plan, organizational structure, and draft background investigations procedures manual. The GRA is implementing a new organizational structure that includes functional descriptions and position descriptions. The GRA agreed to establish a new petroleum revenue audit unit and approved OTA’s proposal outlining the mission statement, organizational structure, staffing and action plan. Work in helped the GRA further solidify reforms in progress. A draft petroleum revenue audit manual and related implementation procedures is helping to prepare the staff at the new petroleum audit unit to begin more sophisticated audit work. (EGCI funding for the petroleum audit work concluded in October 2018.) Introduction of GRA-wide performance management and evaluation systems, leadership training for managers and other critical HR measures support a revitalized human resources organization. A combination of on-the-job and classroom based training at the new Special Investigation Unit (SIU) helps ensure investigators have the skills to effectively implement anti-corruption measures critical to boosting public confidence in the GRA. In 2019, work will include delivery of an extensive classroom-based and on-the-job training program for new recruits at the nascent petroleum audit section, beginning with basic audit and including petroleum industry practices. In HR, OTA will provide guidance on the introduction of GRA-wide performance management and evaluation systems, deliver leadership training for managers and supervisors, and help rewrite job descriptions and other critical HR measures, to support ambitious hiring plans. In anti-corruption, OTA will deliver advanced classroom-based and on-the-job training at the SIU, to equip investigators with the skills to effectively implement anti-corruption measures and boost public confidence in the GRA. OTA will also provide guidance on the implementation of a new organizational structure and the creation of a second deputy position to ensure effective management of these critical and simultaneous reforms.. description.narrative: Guyana's economic growth, resulting from the expansion of its mining sectors, has not resulted in improved social and political development indicators. Challenges to Guyana's development persist, including weak infrastructure, deficiencies in its anti-money laundering and anti-terrorist financing regime, persistent crime, limited law enforcement capacity, drug trafficking, continued out-migration, and the ongoing threat from the HIV/AIDS epidemic. U.S. assistance to Guyana focuses on strengthening democratic institutions, improving citizen security, combatting illicit trafficking, and mitigating the impact of the HIV/AIDS epidemic through the promotion of local, sustainable country programs. Regional programs will advance citizen security through the Caribbean Basin Security Initiative in order to complement and enhance U.S. bilateral assistance.
